rComments: textbook is useless; wiki articles give more information. Not a hard class but subjective teaching of pro-Russian view is very bothersome but I guess university knows no better; its like learning about Africa from British persective - you get some information you can believe, especially if you don't know better, but it doesn't give you actual info

Meh professor. His course narrative lacks depth and nuanced analysis. Get more out of a wiki article then his lectures. Good at telling funny anecdotes about Soviet leaders and what not, but not much in the way of actual content. Easy for those who enjoy a quick survey of a events. But the devil is in the details.

The man is a God among Professors. Not only is he one of the best History profs in McGill, but when my laptop was stolen (with all my papers and notes on it) he was extremely kind, understanding, and most of all postponed my essay to be due at a suitable date. As for his teaching methods, he's interesting, extremely clear, and conveys passion
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Gives good feedback', 'Caring']

rComments: He makes the lecture interesting. The TA can be a strict marker but comes to test and exams he will grade them fairly. It might appear as a hard class in beginning but  gives option between research paper and book report. Dnt worry you will be fine just take detailed notes in class. he does not post lecture slides with details just the pictures.

great prof. Though he has an accent he can make mundane things very fun and clear. Makes all aspects of history enjoyable and can fit a lot of work into 2 hour lectures. his lectures make you remember a lot of what he teaches

Clearly a very accomplished prof. Is able to fit in 50 pages of readings in a 2 hour class, making it very interesting. The one set back is he's a bit stingy on the marking department, so put in some extra work! Other than that I highly recommend him as a teacher:)
